303":"1303","1214":"1214","1236":"1236","1235":"1235","1232":"1232","about 1214":"about 1214","1318":"1318","Normanton, Yorkshire, England":"Normanton, Yorkshire, England","Buckenham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Buckenham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Great Massingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Great Massingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Hilborough, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Hilborough, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cailly","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French:","topographic name for a person living on a patch of pebbly or stony soil, from Old French <i>caillou</i> ‘pebble, stone’, a word of Celtic origin. Compare   Lacaille   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Currier","meanings":["English: occupational name for a person who dressed leather after it was tanned, from Middle English <i>curr(e)iour</i> (Old French <i>conreeur</i> ‘currier’).","Americanized form of French <b>Caillé</b> (see   Caille   3) and <b>Carrière</b> (see   Carriere  )."]},{"name":"Lacaille","meanings":["French:","metonymic occupational name for someone who caught and sold quails, a variant of   Caille   2, with fused feminine definite article <i>la</i>.","topographic name for a person living on a patch of pebbly or stony soil, a variant of   Caille   1, with fused feminine definite article <i>la</i>; or a habitational name from La Caille, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Lacoy  ."]},{"name":"Caye","meanings":["French (mainly Lorraine): possibly a topographic name from Old French <i>caie</i> ‘sandbank, dike’.","French: nickname from dialect <i>caye</i> ‘sow’.","Possibly also an altered form of French   Caille   or   Caillet   (or of some other like-sounding surname); compare   Caya  ."]},{"name":"Cayer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adelard, Armand, Normand, Jacques, Lucien, Andre, Benoit, Emile, Fernand, Germaine, Jean-Marc, Jean-Marie.","Altered form of French <b>Caillé</b> (see   Caille   3). Compare   Cayea  .","French: from Old French <i>caier</i>, a term denoting a pack of four candles (from Latin <i>quaterni</i>), possibly applied as a metonymic occupational name for a candle merchant."]},{"name":"Caya","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adrien, Aurore, Cecile, Girard, Jacques, Normand.","Altered form of French <b>Cailla</b>, itself a dialect form of   Caille   2 ‘quail’ (or perhaps an altered form of some other similar surname beginning in <i>Caill-</i>) or a habitational name from a minor place called Cailla. Compare   Cayo  ."]},{"name":"Caillet","meanings":["French:","topographic name for a person living on a patch of pebbly or stony soil, or a habitational name from (Le) Caillet, the name of several places in various parts of France, from a diminutive of   Caille   1.","derivative of   Cail   3 ‘curds’, a metonymic occupational name for a dairy worker."]}]},{"name":"Osbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ōs</i> ‘god’ + <i>beorht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It is not now common, but in the earlier 20th century it enjoyed a modest vogue in Britain, being borne for example by the cartoonist  Osbert Lancaster  (  1908–86 ) and the writer  Osbert Sitwell  (  1892–1969 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Osbert Cailly was born in 1214, in Buckenham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Adam de Cailly, was 22 and his mother, Mabel Giffard, was 25. He married Emma Tatteshall in 1235, in Great Massingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. He died in 1275, in Hilborough, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 61, and was buried in Hilborough, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1214–1275":"1214–1275","1236–1286":"1236–1286","–1318